[Mortality and years of potential life lost due to homicide in Colombia, 
1985-2006].

[Article in Spanish]

Moreno C(1), Cendales R.

Author information:
(1)Departamento de Medicina Preventiva y Salud Pública, Universidad Autónoma de 
Madrid, Madrid, España. cmarcems@yahoo.com

OBJECTIVE: Describe the mortality patterns, burden of disease, and mechanisms of 
injury by homicide in Colombia between 1985 and 2006.
METHODS: The official population and mortality databases in Colombia were used. 
Equivalencies of the underlying cause of death were identified and grouped 
according to the shortlists of the Ninth and Tenth Revision of the International 
Classification of Diseases. The years of potential life lost (YPLL), indices of 
YPLL, and crude, adjusted, and specific mortality rates associated with major 
causes and external causes for each sex were calculated. The homicide mechanisms 
were described.
RESULTS: During the study period, a total of 523 870 homicides were recorded 
(484 475 in men and 39 395 in women). Homicides accounted for 13.8% of total 
mortality (21.4% of mortality in men and 2.6% in women) and generated 24.2% of 
YPLL (35.2% in men and 5.8% in women). The highest rates in men were found in 
the 20-44-year age range, with specific rates of up to 366.9 per 100 000 
population, and in women in the 15-40 years age range with specific rates of up 
to 24.9 per 100 000 population. The most frequent homicide mechanism in both 
sexes was firearms.
CONCLUSION: Homicides represent a significant burden of disease in Colombia, 
particularly affecting the young male population. Mortality from homicide has 
trended downward in recent years.

