HIV infection and bone disease: implications for an aging population.

Cotter AG(1), Mallon PW.

Author information:
(1)HIV Molecular Research Group, School of Medicine & Medical Science, 
University College Dublin 7, Ireland. Aoife.cotter@ucdconnect.ie

Now more than ever, the management of age-related problems, from cardiovascular 
morbidity to bone pathology, is increasingly relevant for HIV physicians. Low 
bone mineral density (BMD) and fractures are more common in HIV-infected 
patients. Although a multifactorial aetiology underlies this condition, 
increasing evidence suggests a role for antiretroviral therapy in low BMD, 
especially upon initiation. This review will detail the epidemiology, 
pathogenesis, diagnosis and management of osteoporosis and low BMD in 
HIV-infected patients, with particular emphasis on aging.

